SIMPLE: cobble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cobble
<hw>Cob"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fishing boat. See
<er>Coble</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cobble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Cobble
<hw>Cob"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Cob</er> a lump. See
<er>Cob</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 9, and cf. <er>Copple</er>,
<er>Copplestone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cobblestone.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Their slings held <xex>cobbles</xex> round.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Cob coal. See under
<er>Cob</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 272 --></p>

<p><ent>Cobble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Cobble
<hw>Cob"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Cobbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Cobbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>cobler</ets>, <ets>copler</ets>, to join or knit together, couple,
F. <ets>coupler</ets>, L. <ets>copulare</ets> to couple, join. Cf.
<er>Couple</er>, <pos>n.</pos> & <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make or mend coarsely; to patch; to botch; <as>as, to
<ex>cobble</ex> shoes</as>.</def> <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<qex>cobbled</qex> saddle.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Thackeray.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make clumsily.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Cobbled</xex>
rhymes.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pave with cobblestones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cobbler</ent>⟦br⟧
